The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services like their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
He'll probably be here soon.
That the Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) also confirmed the remainder, warning that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the whole of the Union.
The latest steps taken by the European Commission in the field of roaming regulation are likely to lead to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMSs sent from abroad will be cheaper than if sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition on the Czech market.
The Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) Council President Pavel Dvořák has already stated that there is no longer any place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It may be true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find any frequency).
However, there is still one possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market brought a marked price decline, to which the classical operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, you don't have to look too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of the mobile operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
In addition, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, in addition, owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can concentrate on many more specific target groups.
In addition, to operate effectively, they need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not involve relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, these types of virtual operators typically go low-cost - offering cheap calls and SMS messages that, however, are often countered by the more tight service offerings.
For example, mobile Tesco in Britain offers SMS at least half the price compared to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a no-brainer target group can also be a good blow.
This operator is specifically targeting the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - he's the operator he likes and can be trusted with", says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works with this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as that of Poland could be adopted in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubted this: 'The Czech market is relatively small to access by the segments on which most virtual operators rely.
In addition, the supply of services is relatively saturated.'
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is any virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is about the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region", Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, told mobil.cz.
It indirectly assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, they try their best to prevent any potential competition.
Interest in the launch of a mobile virtual operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group which would like to take a step further to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of enterprise customers.
"We are very interested in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephone services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to make progress in meetings", said the group's spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe better times will shine.
It seems that, from unofficial information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly by the end of the year.
But for now, his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is suitable for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market is a very specific market compared to others.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this area", said Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market is also reflected in other operators.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional agreement with O2's opinion, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop".
He adds: "It will be difficult to find any virtual operators on T-Mobile's network until the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table some concrete contract that would be possible to study in such a short horizon".
Vodafone is focusing its attention rather on meeting the requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of spending and infrastructure sharing.
We consider it precisely the greatest contribution from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area lies in the partner with whom it establishes a shared network for fast mobile internet.'
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increased competition which would lead to a drop in prices and, therefore, a decrease in profits.
Then why facilitate entry into competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of that is the lamb when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on the ČTÚ was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is attested to by the public information available on the ČTÚ's website.
But right now U:fon is an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: "Moreover, the competitive environment in the mobile market has recently opened up to a fourth operator.
As regards the nature of the mobile telephone market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would entail high requirements for the latter and, in particular, for its services.'
This is why this access to mobile operators is extremely discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to enter into commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This is purely the case with the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tender (OTC).
However, the Commission expressed its typical attitude to this problem.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator is concluded.
To date no agreement has been concluded as the offer of the potential interested parties was not interesting enough for the classic operators", added Kristián Chalupa, of the UOHS's Department of External Relations.
These statements do not surprise the operators' representatives.
For the offices which are supposed to represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, but they should also note that no one is taking advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the foreign countries where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the fall in prices of mobile telephony services"
The pressure on the proper functioning of the market and the fall in prices are not in the interest of the OHIM.
The really dramatically shocking thing about this whole case is the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it's really a coincidence, it comes up on its own.
The same is true of the price of gasoline at petrol stations, as it is clearly the result of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
'The Office has found no signs of unfair competition in this respect and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position and therefore do not have a corresponding increase in liability for their market activities.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as well as telecommunications regulators", Chalupa added to his answer.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is clearly a relevant market analysis carried out by ČTÚ according to which telecommunications are, from the point of view of commercial tendering, a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for a virtual operator to emerge, agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator - with all his logic - has a monopoly on his network.
In a particular segment, therefore, it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for UOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators are rising dramatically in similar fashion.
The current complaints of the interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators many similar obstacles are encountered.
The responsibility to the CTU is a fairly common trick in the telecommunications sector from which the OHIM washes its hands in all this matter.
We've met him before in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Law was recently introduced to increase the competence of the ČTÚ in the field of commercial tenders, which did not take effect, even though a number of experts promised that the situation would improve.
This should be well known to the representatives of the OHIM, but it is clear that their interests lie elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one's looking
At the same time, it is still working subtly as a pseudovirtual operator that there are already a few in Czech mobile phone networks.
They are companies that set their own prices for mobile services, but only a part of them are public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a select few get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same by ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases like those cited were discovered, it could be said that the terms of the contract were breached and that this could lead to the end of the cooperation with the company", Martina Kemrová said.
But it is quite unlikely that such activity by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
In the case of the three companies mentioned above, it may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
The activities of these companies generate not insignificant profits and, at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the potential problems: "The law allows for such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
They must also accept that their phone's SIM card is not in their name and therefore cannot have it at all as a normal customer of the operators".
This is precisely what the CTU should think is minimally strange.
A new question for the OHIM also appears.
If mobile phone operators are blindsided in this kind of procedure, why block the virtual operator's entry?
It must be added that the OHIM has sufficient competence to discover these types of activities and if it is not willing it must not be content with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this history and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As already clear from the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market brought a significant drop in the prices of services.
At the same time, in virtually every country where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators tried to protect themselves more or less from this breakout.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, eventually too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the more advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have intervened at this time and in none of the cases have defended the operators but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to bring about the first virtual operator and with it others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Authority is handling this whole case like a burning nail.
We cannot help but wonder if the confusion of attributions in these cases is a good fit.
But let's not despair.
If this information behind the scenes is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market is probably starting to move again.
If any of the operators allows a virtual mobile operator to enter it will be difficult for the OHIM to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one.
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the official Czech anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolanek on the occasion of the official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, My Home.
The new anthem was recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solo, one for male and one for female, one with Choir and one instrumental.
The singing is handled by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the arrangements of the hymn are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national anthem to be one of the most beautiful.
The Czech Radio has already said before that it intentionally chose for the Solos singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I have tried with the two and then, also, with the Choir to fix themselves in the diction so that the text was well understood, so that it had consonance", he commented.
The official Czech anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, My Home was first played in 1834 on the stages of the States Theatre in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it their own.
The first stanza of the song after the rise of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
