The Prague MHD takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday 1 October 2008, the history of the Prague Transport Company records the date when the first passengers enter the subway, tram and bus with an electronic bonus in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can be purchased at this time by almost 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously upload it to their chip card at the transport company's info centres and stations at the Metro, Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka stations.
The bonds can be purchased online from yesterday on the transport company's website, www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred people until the afternoon.
Those who start using the Internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget about ticket stations at metro stations, where until now they had to line up regularly to get a normal ticket.
The voucher is purchased online, and the Opencard card is recharged at one of the 13 local library branches.
"In these places there is a window with prepared staff available to passengers that helps those interested in buying online and also with the recharging of the bonus purchased on their card", said the project spokesman, Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to recharge the electronic bonus on the Opencard in vending machines located in some metro hallways.
What are these vending machines like?
They are red, reminiscent of a ticket machine and travellers will probably have already noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská subway stations.
"There are now five in the city but by the end of the year there should be eighty", Opatrný said.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Just put the Opencard chip card in it and the previously paid bonus will be charged only on it.
The e-bonds from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
That is, on the commuter trains and bus lines from the numbers 300 to 499 which are mainly used by the inhabitants of the towns of central Bohemia.
"In trains connected to Prague's integrated transportation there are reviewers equipped with a reader card that will help confirm the validity of the time and the zone of the bonus", said the ticket controller Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization that sets the schedules for Prague's collective transportation.
Circuit buses have their reading cards mounted on the driver's cab.
When entering the car, you must not only show the driver the card but also accompany him with the Opencard at the place designated for that purpose on the side of the box.
The driver then controls the validity of the bond.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonds there is nothing easier than to ask the driver for this information", Drápal completed.
Passengers who do not travel on the round-trip buses and do not remember when the bonus expires can go to the vending machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the screen of the machine, you will be shown the information about the validity of your document.
The Southeast wanted to be part of the US in a referendum
The German Sudetes demanded in 1945 that Fumaba be part of the United States.
This is what is extracted from the letter that is kept in the collection of the South Bohemian Science Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to at least live under the patronage of the United States of America.
This is what some Sudeten German groups presumably addressed to the President of the United States in 1945.
It is the result of the letters that are kept in a private archive and that are today kept in the collection of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Český Krumlov request in a letter to the American president not to allow the return of the "Sumava land" - occupied by Hitler under the Munich Pact - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and we really want your word that American units are coming to German lands not as oppressors or enemies but as liberators", the letter, signed with a "people who carry the fate of Šumava in their hearts", reads.
Since the union of Czechoslovakia with the German south-east presumably represents - according to these the Czech national character - a hope only in brutality, disregard, incomprehension, pressure and slavery, the authors plead in the letter with the American president to assume for today and forever Šumava under a protectorate.
"We cannot believe that without considering the opinion of four million inhabitants, he will hand us over to a foreign state that oppresses and rejects minorities and that in no way contributes to the victory of the allies", the letter says.
The authors' inability to sign is presumably due to fear of reprisals from the "Czech oppressors".
If the US president were presumably in doubt about this idea of the German Shumavas, it would be enough to hold a referendum on whether their inhabitants want to be part of the US or live under its patronage.
Although the text of the letter, with the current knowledge of postwar history, may sound a little childish, some specialists say it paints neatly on the expectations of the Germans in the southeast at the time.
Although the Czech Germans had to have a slight sense that their expulsion from the republic was going to be discussed, only a few admitted this possibility.
Some hoped that the United States and Britain would negotiate for the Sudetenland some clear form of autonomy.
Others thought they would stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is even confirmed by the Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
This one was in the war, as German Budějovice, enlisted in the Baltic Navy.
When the British captured him at the end of the war and placed him in the Holstein prison camp, dozens of Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They thought that when they came home, the Czech would be good for them", Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, he said, expected that under the Benes Decrees they would be removed from the Republic.
