Rats have feelings too
They say a rat or cockroach feeling danger flee, why is he also afraid?
Joseph Le Doux, a neuroscientist, is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
How can we control whether they, behaving in a similar way to us, feel the same way?
For many years, an online magazine called "Edge" has been publishing contributions from famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of selected answers to the question What do you think is true without being able to prove it?
I think animals have sensations and other states of consciousness that I or anyone else could not prove until now, although we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case at least we can expect it because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But as soon as we get into other species and include questions about sensation and consciousness in general, we enter the unknown realm because the hardware doesn't match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as the other animals: it makes itself dead, runs away or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, which is why some scientists draw conclusions about comparable subjective experience.
I don't think so, of course.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to infect our subjective experience with that of animals.
First, they almost always include the circuits associated with human consciousness from the lateral prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex (due to their involvement in short memory and executive functions that direct behavior).
This broad part is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be absolutely missing in other creatures.
Taking into account at least the aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex, including our knowledge of who we are and our ability to plan and decide, there is reason to suppose that even humans are different from other primates.
Another peculiarity lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since most of his experience is linked to language, it often means that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals may be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not dependent on language, it would influence it in such a way that the consciousness of animals, created as it is, would in many cases differ from most of our states of consciousness.
That's why it's hard to explain how other animals' consciences work.
If that, as something interesting and subjective, is not allowed to be measured because it has the special hardware, or allowed to be analyzed through our experiences, then their research presents us with big problems.
Most of my speeches concern the content of conscious experience, but at the same time there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be easier for scientific research.
You could research the processes of animal consciousness without taking into account their contents, and that's what happens during short-memory primate studies, especially in the example of visualization.
But with this approach that Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, the essence goes more to the neutral correlates of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: the two may or may not be alike.
Interestingly, this approach highlights the importance of the prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex for the formation of visualization.
And what's the effect on the sensations?
I owe it to the fact that in the emotional system, a part of the brain is activated that is responsible for that, the same thing that happens with fear.
What we describe as fear is therefore a state of mind in which we are when brain activity occupies a space of the defense system (or its consequences such as body reactions).
From this point of view, sensations are very fixed apart from the cerebral cortex, which distinguishes primates and especially humans.
From the point of view of linguistic nature, fine sensation classifications follow because we can differentiate and classify states using words and grammar to describe the states of others alongside ourselves.
For example, Antonio Damasco, on the contrary, thinks that sensations are derived from the simple activities of the parts of the cerebral cortex responsible for bodily feelings and the brainstem, as does Jaak Pankseep, but focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much during human evolution, it can refer to absolutely different types and their sensations.
For theoretical reasons I cannot go against that, but I consider it unlikely.
Pakseep argues that what rats and men feel like fear, possibly feels like that in two cases as well: But how can you control whether rats and men behaving similarly feel the same way?
Seeing danger, a cockroach flies, because he's afraid?
I am of the opinion that the similarity of behaviour does not yet prove the similarity of experience.
That's true, the neural comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brainstems, but cockroaches don't have at least one brain.
Is the brainstem responsible for sensations?
Even if it's possible to test it for men, how can you test it for rats?
I think rats and other mammals, possibly cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don't know how you can prove it.
I prefer to investigate rat emotional behavior over emotional sensations because their sensations are supposedly fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness refers to special circuits and language).
In any case, progress in neurology is expected here as long as the same is measured in rats and men.
Since I don't research the language and consciousness of rats, as well as sensations, I don't know if they exist.
I can't see past my nose, you might say, but I'd rather move forward than work permanently without results.
Well, I'm a practical emotionalist.
