The price has dropped more than $20 a barrel since last Monday.
In the last two weeks, commodity markets have been shaken by the financial crisis on Wall Street and a couple of powerful hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After reaching a high of $145.29 a barrel in July, prices had fallen to nearly $90 a barrel earlier this month, before falling back again, due to the enormous uncertainty in financial markets.
Anxiety seized investors once again on Monday, despite congressional leaders saying they had reached an agreement over the weekend on the largest bailout in history.
The news was overshadowed by new concerns that the financial crisis was far from over.
The latest developments in the merger process confirm that Citigroup will buy the Wachovia Corporation's banking operations, according to government statements on Monday.
Meanwhile, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalized the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
Analysts at Barclays Capital said that, in the frantic weekend, the negotiations that led to the rescue deal "seemed unable to revive market sentiment".
As the economic situation deteriorates, demand for commodities, including oil, is expected to drop.
"The outlook for global equity, interest rates and exchange rates will be increasingly uncertain", Deutsche Bank analysts wrote in a note to investors.
"We believe that commodities cannot escape this contagion.
From a product perspective, our most pressing concern is the assessment of whether the American virus will spread globally and specifically to China".
Bank analysts have lowered their expectations for the coming year, as oil consumption declines due to the economic growth crisis and the forecast for a 20 percent drop in oil and gas prices by 2009.
