Hidden by the expansion of the park to the great Orlando, a few miles from the bright, noisy and colossal city, lies a quiet village, where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are very evident.
Eatonville, the first fully black-populated city incorporated into the country and the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 black men, 300 good swimmers, many gay bars, two schools and not a prison".
It's now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! fair in Eatonville to pay tribute to Mrs. Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, in many ways, the city she described  making it also a tourist stage by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Federal Writers Project during the Depression season - remains a separate place.
The city remains independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Mrs. Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their true ideas with the white man, who "knows so little about us and doesn't know what he's missing".
Even now, in the year that a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, has drawn attention to starting a dialogue on the issue of race, many remain cautious in the face of the outsider.
"We're very careful about the way our story is told", said Jones Hortense, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city's oldest church.
"It has to be right".
Eatonville has always been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It's also a historical model of the affirmation of blacks and a community of nearly 2,400 people living below a poverty level twice the national average.
It's a literary center, but also a fine example of the rural culture of the black South - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that was born of slavery in America.
No wonder the people here are both proud and reserved.
And the concern for Eatonville's image really started with Zora, as nobody here calls her Mrs. Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through her profound dialect books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a road that runs through central Florida often forgotten inside black history and human drama.
With a concrete face in both life and literature, Mrs. Hurston took her readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then into more private areas.
"Outside the road on the left hand", he wrote, "there is the modern brown public school with its white finishes, its well-kept gardens and playgrounds, cared for by Howard Miller, as he can barely read and write".
She also mentions the widow Dash's new husband and writes that Glenn Lee "sells drinks of all kinds and anything goes with transitory rooms".
So in just a few hundred words Mrs Hurston relates Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Obviously, this Fodor didn't.
In fact, not everyone appreciated the portrait.
"Zora described it as it was", said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's girls that Mrs. Hurston immortalized citing men who were singing colorless songs about their beauty.
He added: "Some people didn't like that".
Mrs. Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who returned frequently after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Franklin Augusto, 77, remembers that when Mrs. Hurston arrived in town, she did so without warning in a large Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still today prides itself on wearing dignity.
Most residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin said, while many laughed sarcastically.
"People were always very happy to see Zora", Mr. Franklin continues.
But, he adds, swinging in his chair in a backyard overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Mrs. Hurston was probably baptized, "she never stayed too long".
When Mrs. Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were no longer in print.
Like most of the world, Eatonville also seemed to have forgotten about her.
Although she was a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only woman of color at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce - Florida, where she had been living.
In Eatonville, there were no large commemorative ceremonies, no large public readings.
"I don't think her contribution to the world or her legacy was understood", said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography of Mrs. Hurston published in 2003.
A certain twist came in the '80s.
Orange County officials wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the main two-lane street of the labor community.
