"Capture the master off stage to extract his character" Günther Bauer_Photographer
No heels or flyers or opening costumes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration in interpretation to obtain the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
Next to the artist.
The other, the person.
They're inseparable except in privacy, in those moments outside the public, when they find the privacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of a handful, careless because they're not going to come out on stage.
German Günther Bauer alternates in "Flamenco-people" the theatrical nature of some stages with singers, dancers and guitarists with that lesser known side of these masters.
With this proposal, the photographer collects the particular iconography of flamenco from different fields.
Included in the programming of the Flamenco Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, increasing every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco-people" "can be any people but, when viewing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists on stage.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists capable of conveying passion, sadness, joy on stage... captivating the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, you don't have to take pictures of the stage.
They carry their personality and character inside.
What interested me was creating an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the great flamenco players with the camera".
With the flavor of the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to portray singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
They are portraits that, due to the selection of the camera and the material, remind of classical photography.
The application of different stylistic media breaks with the classical basis of the image, giving it modernity, an idea that reflects how Bauer himself understands flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots, which evolves and surprises every day".
It is not the act of dance, singing or touch itself, but the artist's personality, his character, that captures the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential, with the creature that becomes visible in a way of feeling, of being and of being is and has been the constant of this work that is presented these days in the gallery El Fotomata.
Known figures of the flamenco such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, configure this selection of almost seventy photographed artists.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited in the exhibition.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with "SportARTproject" ("Portraits of Veteran Athletes").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "I love to portray people, to meet them and to be able to enter an instant into their lives, whether a long or short one.
I think that within photography, portraiture is the most difficult genre.
You meet or face people, characters, who sometimes you don't even know, or who only leave you a few minutes to take a photo.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true".
This collection of contemporary flamenco portraits entitled "Flamenco-people" is on display at the Fotomata Gallery, located at 20 de la calle de la Mata, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, where you can visit until October 16.
