'Blood of May', the epic gamble of Garci
Inspired by the National Episodes of Benito Pérez Galdós, José Luis Garci recreates the famous uprising of the Spanish against the French in Sangre de Mayo, which is the most ambitious film in his filmography with a budget of about 15 million euros.
In this way, the filmmaker has tried to "illustrate the torrent of characters and social analysis" that he has always admired in the work of the well-known novelist, he explained today during the presentation of the film, with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría at the head of a large cast of performers.
Blood of May, with a footage of more than two and a half hours, is set to premiere this Friday in cinemas, to become a future mini-series for Telemadrid of more than four hours.
A great admirer of Galdós's literature, José Luis Garci says he has fulfilled this shooting "a childhood dream", which he must thank Esperanza Aguirre, who from the Community of Madrid commissioned him three years ago to shoot a commemorative film for the second centenary of May 2nd in Madrid, something he accepted as long as the story was based on the National Episodes.
The 15 million budget that the Community of Madrid has contributed in its entirety is a "unique opportunity" for Garci to portray with decorated and appropriate clothing the portrait of "an atoll-bound Spain that was mistaken as the boss to fight for, since the struggle for independence led the people to enormous delay with the reign of Fernando VII", he said.
But the filmmaker regrets not having had a financing like Alatriste or Los fantasmas de Goya - more than twice that of Sangre de mayo-, so he has not been able to shoot some scenes in a script signed with Horacio Valcárcel, with whom he has collaborated almost all his career.
The director of "Return to Start" has therefore focused on his usual way of working, staging with the actors, with whom he usually rehearses before starting filming and those who do not cast, because he considers it "humiliating" and considers that "part of the director's job is to go to the theater and cinema to learn what happens in the industry in which he works".
Many of the performers he matches in Sangre de Mayo repeat before his camera, as is the case of Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larrañaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
A four-time Oscar nominee - one of which he won -, Garci believes that any of the three candidates to represent Spain this year before the Hollywood Academy, the May Blood, Seven French Billiard Tables and the final selected, The Blind Sunflowers, do not represent a young generation of Spanish cinema, "which is the one that should be known", he said.
With this movie, Garci doesn't expect any prizes.
"In the beginning you think you work for posterity, then you realize you only work for prosperity, and now you settle for making another film", explains Garci after more than 30 years of professional career.
Isabel Bayón recovers the essence of the Sevillian dancer Tórtola Valencia
A Sevillian dancer is going to pay tribute to a Sevillian dancer.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia, of Catalan father (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana neighborhood and when she was three years old moved to London with her family.
She was a freestyle dancer and a specialist in oriental dance.
She had an exciting life, pioneering the liberation of women, like Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and vegetarian and advocated for the abolition of the corset that prevented women's free movement.
The life of this woman who marked a dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe between the wars, fascinated Isabel Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she proposed this character to me and I thought it was amazing".
According to the dancer, "we don't intend to tell her life but to pick up her spirit.
The titles of their dances have suggested flamenco sticks to me.
So, "the butterfly dance" suggested a guajira, or "the snake dance" a few tangos.
Their dance was sensual and I've been told that my dance is also within this aesthetic", she says.
The installation features two exceptional collaborations: that of Miguel Poveda who will sing again to Isabel in one of his shows, as he did in "The open door"; and with the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to collaborate with whoever was his student.
"Matilde makes Torttola the senior, the character of maturity.
I'm happy that you've accepted to act in my play and I'm very honored".
The installation also features the musical composition and guitars of Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, the song of Miguel Ortega, the Pulga and Moi de Morón; the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa El Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfra Juárez, "who plays the role of the eternal companion of this type of artists who were divas in all their extension, and who are always in love with them".
The work also tells of the life of this woman who developed in places so far away, especially for the time, such as India, the United States, or Russia, as well as throughout Europe, since she habitually resided in London.
"I wanted to remind her because I think she is one of those women who have a huge influence in a given era and now nobody knows and much less values her work", says Bayon.
The show will start today at 20.30 at the Lope de Vega theatre.
