Drivers who have a relapse due to alcoholism must install the 'alcolock'
Interior wants the driver with three administrative penalties for alcoholism to have a system installed in his vehicle that prevents the vehicle from starting drunk, or if it doesn't blow.
The initiative was announced last June and is now included in the annual report of the State Attorney General, which says it is a pilot project that will last one year.
The purpose of the training is to reintegrate the driver, so he will also receive a road re-education course.
In addition to the Attorney General for Road Safety, the Directorate General of Traffic (DGT) and the Foundation Institute of Technology for Automotive Safety (FITSA) will participate in the experience.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of drivers who are reported to have been drunk more than once return to their cars.
The alcolock would prevent this as it is a vehicle-connected system that measures the alcohol rate in exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not blow abtes; or when a concentration of alcohol is detected above the permitted.
It costs more than 1,000 euros and would be paid for by the sanctioned person.
In this respect, a 2007 US study showed that vehicles equipped with these devices reduce infringements by up to 65% during the first year of deployment.
And in Spain, it's estimated that it could save 115 lives every year.
The measure is subject to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address these behaviours before they lead to criminal offences.
The Commission has also proposed that the Commission should be able to implement the reforms in the field of criminal law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although it has already been experimentally deployed in some industrial and public service vehicles.
The Congress of Deputies will vote tomorrow on an initiative by the PSOE to install this system in school buses, as has been done in France.
