Speaking in your sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up very freaked out telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while they're sleeping.
The first time it happens you might get scared, but it doesn't really matter.
It's a benign sleep disturbance called sleepwalking.
It's quite common, especially in children and teenagers.
I'm sure more than one person has heard that you spoke at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life for example associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nighttime nausea (going to sleep) or sleepwalking, but they don't have to be.
As we mentioned earlier, they can also be associated with very high fever patterns, stressful situations or over-excitement.
It's a little-studied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
He may speak in a calm tone of voice, loose words, a murmur, or the opposite (crying, crying, long speeches, etc.).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if there is any issue that is generating much anxiety and thus gives him a way out.
We've said it's a benign disorder, so it's not treatable unless it's associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (e.g. if it's associated with sleep apnea or a stressful picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to bed.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or slightly violent.
With children who are very nervous and who have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a measure of inner calm.
This will help the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
Once the sleepwalks appear, try to stay calm.
Remember, they're harmless to the child and the next day he won't remember anything about what happened.
Useful Tips
You didn't wake him.
It's useless, because he's unconscious, and you'll break his sleep.
Even though he's talking, he's asleep and therefore resting.
Remember, if you are feeling very anxious for several episodes, you should consult or find out what is causing such anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not the usual), do not be tempted to ask him questions to get information.
You'll get nothing, because as you sleep, you're not conscious enough to organize your thinking.
You will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say, so be careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the kid you can question him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even a joke.
That's a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's not bad at all, it's an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
