Interview - Blood is safe again
HEMA-Québec was celebrating its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to be happy, because HEMA-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And most of all, it regained the public's trust that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, to clarify the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would not recur.
While Judge Krever was delayed in presenting his report, certain provinces then set up a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
Following the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been set up in Canada: Hema-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when HEMA-Québec began its activities, almost 38 percent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, recalls Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
After making many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and much work over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence", he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Decary recalls, however, that "confidence is extremely fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, HEMA-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were witnessing the birth in Europe of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, Decary says.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
We then rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we don't know and when a serious disease can arise from that, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But a few years ago, it was proved beyond a doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle applied made sense".
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV screening technique was introduced: nucleic acid tests that allow the presence of the virus to be directly detected in the blood of donors, rather than antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used up to now were based.
Nucleic acid tests shortened the time between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
We can substantially reduce the risk that certain donors are unwittingly infected and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS by blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"That means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before anyone is infected with HIV.
So since HEMA-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products every year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission from a blood product occurs.
I believe that you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health without worries today", says the head of the management of HEMA-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
You never know what pathogen might emerge in the system.
Last year, Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant", Dr. Décary continues, before stressing that in addition to safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for sufficient supply.
"Needs increase as the population ages.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a red blood cell or platelet injection.
The aging population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average only groups 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation".
However, all healthy people aged 18 and above who meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is rampant, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
Hardship is very rare.
But the members of this network of donors need to be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
But it's hard to convince people to donate their blood, but most importantly to keep them and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since today's life is so rampant, we rarely find time to spend an hour donating their blood", says Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, HEMA-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec, which also operates the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases like leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, the bank placement of our 1,000th umbilical cord blood sample and are expected to draw more than 1,000 of these a year.
We should start proposing it for grafts early next year", says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this", since HEMA-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in every hospital in Quebec.
