What did they produce at the Zuschlag &amp; Co. invoice factory?
Soon, on October 8, criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing significant damage to the economy, continuously and in an organized manner, and other crimes, including forgery of documents.
According to the Prosecutor's Office, they used the funds obtained in public competitions for their own purposes, often justifying the fulfillment of the tasks with false invoices.
The public and municipal funds - in total about HUF 65 million - were partly held by the Fiatal Baloldal organization and partly by private individuals.
The method, which was also made public by the investigators, was to justify the collection of funds obtained from public tenders with false invoices behind which there was no actual execution, the various associations never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the prosecution, most of the bills were fake.
For this they obtained the talons at the market in the Józsefváros District and the circular stamps were manufactured in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question of which company to make the counterfeit invoice was decided among others on that tour of the Upper Balaton Region where János Zuschlag sent István Lados.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for a bill for his consumption and these served as a model to make the bills they presented among others in the contests of the Ministry of Youth Affairs and Sports, in the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labor, as well as in the City Council of the Capital.
These bills were mostly signed by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who according to our information was writing the reports needed to obtain the public subsidies.
During one of his "study trips" Lados chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this food centre provided food for a group of ninety people from Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However, according to the center's manager, not many people fit in at the same time.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation - later called Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért - was full of formal and contextual errors.
A hostel in Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, yet the bill was one hundred and thirty people.
But the big-fantastic billmakers also exaggerated when they pointed to the Pigal Kft. food centre, because in the possession of books of the same - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, informed hvg.hu that when he was summoned by the prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he already knew that they were fake documents.
"The name of our company and the NIF were in the wrong place on the stamp".
He added that, in addition to the formal problems, he also did not agree that according to the bill, 100 people were accommodated, since they have only 11 rooms in which not so many people fit.
In addition, the bill also included meals, while the restaurant has been out of business for a long time.
The enthusiastic invoice makers were also not informed that the travel agency chosen in Budapest organises exclusively travel abroad, so that in the cash payment invoice they foolishly indicated as a service a trip within Hungary, which was not in line with the agency's invoice-issuing practice.
In addition, as was known during the investigation, VAT was also included in the document, although travel outside the European Union was tax-free.
The VAT measure was also incorrect in the four documents issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, since the services of that company are not charged with a 25 but only with 15 percent VAT, and the hotel employees only issued invoices made by machine, but the invoice was manual.
In addition, the 'expeditors' made other mistakes as well, such as in the case of a company in which they put on the invoice as activity carried out by road transport which - it became known during the investigations of the prosecutor's office - does not carry out the company founded as investment consultant.
Similarly, due to formal differences - inadequate form of the invoice, false stamp - it was known that the invoices issued for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and for Biztos Pont were false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied having issued those invoices.
The counterfeiters also paid attention to the fact that when the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület ate there (2001) the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation process, so the person in charge of the liquidation process - according to our information - denied having issued such a document.
They deliberately dispatched the bills.
Another group of fake invoice makers is made up of those who were aware that they should issue fake invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, issued an invoice worth about HUF four million on behalf of the Együtt Foundation to Harmadik Évezredért.
The manager of Collab Kft. - according to the prosecution - was convinced by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue fictitious invoices.
In addition, Biogate Kft. was also involved in the liquidation process with Zuschlag and its partners, which in 2003 supplied invoices worth approximately HUF 5 million to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association, with no real economic activity behind it.
There was no movement of capital either, as they later annulled the prepared invoices but forgot to make this entity listed in their documents.
The next group of fake invoice makers includes those who have some connection to the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was the plaintiff of the Ukrainian manager of the fictitious Delta Trio SL based in Budapest, which was engaged in the fuel and vehicle trade.
This company issued numerous invoices for the sale of IT media in the months of October, November and December 2005 worth approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation data, these invoices were purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The manager of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov should have also dispatched documents relating to the company between 2002 and 2005.
We have information that Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices for Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt on behalf of the company to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány collecting the amount himself.
Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. were founded by Romanian bricklayers at the express request of Ivan Kubatov.
However, none of the companies actually worked because - according to the defendant - they were not given jobs.
But he took advantage of these companies, since at the request of his accomplice, lawyer Zsolt Szente, who prepared the company registration documents, they issued invoices on behalf of the companies for the organizations linked to Zuschlag: for Atlasz and for Y-Generáció.
Kubatov, on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trio, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, issued a total of 15 invoices to different entities for a value of HUF 14.2 million.
The Prosecutor's Office considered that Kubatov received VAT and 10% of the invoice amount.
That man even used the company in commandite Szi-Beri to issue fictitious invoices used in Biztos Pont's contest.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted a tender in January 2006 to Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA), a public utility entity of the Socialist Party.
They received 500 thousand HUF respectively from the contest, but did not use the money for the purposes of the contest.
To keep this from being discovered, they presented to the TMA five fictitious invoices received from the Works Team Kft.
These were the invoices found during the registration of the office that Árpád Kemecsei had at the headquarters of the Ministry of Education.
Some of the defendants will probably report at trial - as they did at the Prosecutor's Office - the course of counterfeiting the invoices.
The most interesting thing could be the confession of the main accused himself, János Zuschlag, if he decides to dismantle everything.
For his confessions so far have not been very detailed and although he has repeatedly promised to talk about everything, this has not done so until now.
The question is, what interest does he have in doing so? Perhaps in return for the return of most of the money - HUF 50 million - the socialists reached an agreement with him to have Zusi assume all the responsibilities.
Who, on the other hand, for these days could even offend himself, since to alleviate his prison conditions he requested house arrest, but was repeatedly denied.
While the numerous perpetrators of economic crimes of much higher value, who never returned the money, walk freely or at least can wait in their own homes for sentencing, he has no chance for that.
Overlapping psychology: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University have discovered the neurological - economic - basis for this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people don't want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups was playing lottery, the other was taking part in an auction, and in the meantime the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) system was examining the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games participants could win money, but during auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called the stratum located below the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, along with many other functions, plays a role in the nervous system's "self-reward" mechanism.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in stakes is explained as a prevention to avoid provoking an intense reaction of the stratum.
To support their theory, the economists in the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product concerned and its members made a bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 in prize money.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but if they lost the auction, the group members lost even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one, victory was highlighted and for the other, failure.
However, testing the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the "failure-versus-failure" group were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
'These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
The Commission has therefore decided to take the necessary measures to ensure that the Community's financial resources are not used to finance the sale of goods.
Only visual neurological methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation". - said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When should you see a doctor?
Worldwide, about 500 million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 are being treated because many of the patients do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common name for various liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause are very different.
Hepatitis virus dependent on the pathogen is spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (sperm, vaginal humor, saliva).
Travellers are advised to protect themselves with vaccines against A and B viruses, there are no vaccines against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and white of the eyes, the excrement becomes clear, the urine is dark in color and the healing can take two to three weeks.
Every year, one million people die worldwide from cancer and cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected people receives drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment, it can cause cirrhosis of the liver and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know they are sick because this pathogen gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early detection, systematic medical checks are very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and tattooed people.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
Since this disease can be detected with routine laboratory testing as well, it is worth consulting with your family doctor if you experience any unknown symptoms.
The disease has a cure if it's discovered in time, it's possible to exterminate the virus from the organism, so you can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organisations representing the sick.
The aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of early recognition.
Does it hurt less for those who believe in God?
According to a recent study, religious faith has a calming effect that also relieved the deaths of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment: They analyzed how religious belief influences human pain, reports the British newspaper Telegraph.
In this unique experiment, they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scan technique, it was verified that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
This experiment is the first in a series of research projects involving scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University.
The analysis was as follows: They fixed a sparkling instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings: the Virgin Mary, a 17th-century work by Sassoferrato, and the 15th-century Lady of the Harpoon by Leonardo da Vinci.
The researchers hoped that the Virgin Mary show would evoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a calming effect.
Patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts during that period while looking at the religious painting or the other.
Catholics claimed that by looking at the Virgin Mary they felt "safe" as "protected" people, "calmed down and peace reigned in their hearts".
When they looked at the religious subject painting, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image that is so shocking, you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positively, like a mother or a father", the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"Exercising faith should and in many cases does change our personality", Wright added.
After these formidable results, one question remains: What effect would it have on pain regulation if Leonardo's Madonna or another painter of his size were shown to the faithful?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
