The smart car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method of developing technologies to prevent collisions, if not to imitate obstacle sensors in nature?
For example, the bumblebee.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC Japan, the bumblebees gave Nissan engineers the starting point for designing the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the BR23C type of nature-imitating robotic steering system, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During flight, each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, RP and development and research technology director at the exhibition.
The composite eyes of bumblebees play an important role, being able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eyes, engineers used the laser-beam length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 metres at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle's microprocessor which immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle's robot mimics the movements of the bumblebees, changing the direction by turning the wheels as necessary.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If it were not so, the vehicle's robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety-protective capsule, in a layer within which all kinds of collisions are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect what a bumblebee does to avoid other bumblebees.
This process must be done in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of the wheels' rotation
Thus, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the car robot the rotational motion and acceleration plus braking.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh says the important thing is instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the ability to process the data, let alone the storage capacity.
This device every second just needs to process some input signals and react as needed.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data from the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
You don't need gigabytes of memory, you don't need megabytes.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately bypass the obstacles, which according to Nissan's calculations, within ten years will be able to be incorporated into mass-produced models.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding obstacles in his way.
