Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, national industrial sales prices increased by 0.1% compared to last month's prices and by 12.9% compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Statistical Office (KSH).
Industrial export prices increased by 1,1% compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3,9% compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent from the previous month and by 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only by a minimal measure, at 0.1%.
Domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors increased slightly, by 0.1% compared to July.
The largest increase in price volume occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), primarily due to a 4.6 percent monthly increase in bags and belts and a 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of basic plastics and chemicals resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical production sector (1.6%).
The price decline was seen in the petrochemical sector (1.4%), in the production of electrical machinery and instruments (0.9%) and - to a lesser extent - in the wood processing sector (0.1%).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing did not change.
In the rest of the processing industry, prices increased by 0.2 to 0.9%.
The supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent a significant weight in domestic trade, increased by 0.3% in August, primarily as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from 1 July.
In a comparison period of 12 months, the largest increase in prices in the domestic sales of the processing industry was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4%).
The metalworking sector saw an increase of 13.2 percent, while the food, beverage and tobacco industries, which are of decisive weight, saw an increase of 11 percent.
Prices decreased in the textile industry (2.5%) and in the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3%).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1%.
Over the past year, prices in the global processing industry have increased by 10.2 percent.
Prices for electricity, gas, heat and water supplies surpassed previous year's prices by 18.7%.
In August, the largest monthly price increase (0.7%) was recorded in the investment goods sector among the different sectors of domestic trade.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3%, while in the energy and intermediate sectors there was no change from the previous month.
In August 2008, the highest price increase was in the energy and intermediate sectors (16,8%) compared to the same month the previous year.
The consumer goods sector declined by 6.8 per cent and investment goods by 1.4 per cent.
The export prices of the industry calculated in HUF increased by 1,1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3,9 percent.
The national currency's share in one month fell by 1.7 per cent against the euro and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar, compared with August 2007, strengthened by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
