The European Summit on Equality of Opportunities has opened in Paris today. It is hosted by France, which is also the President-in-Office of the European Union this year.
Lívia Járóka, MEP from Fidesz, in her message to the plenary as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that scourge Roma children and also the biggest obstacle to the prevailing foundation of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner responsible for jobs, social affairs and equal opportunities.
Representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European organisations for the protection of social rights attended the meeting.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group of MEPs in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to employment discrimination, Roma are excluded from the labour market primarily because of their low level of education.
"Most young Roma have not completed secondary education and due to the poor quality of basic education, only a small percentage can obtain a university diploma".
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role in the prevailing foundation of other human rights as well.
Investment in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economies of the Member States of the European Union.
The European Parliament has also called for a new framework for the protection of the environment.
The earlier a Gypsy student starts school, the more chances he has of becoming an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and must ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education", said Járóka.
The European Union must be united in its objective and active work to speed up school desegregation immediately, and the correct implementation of existing and planned anti-discrimination directives is of paramount importance.
"We must break the vicious cycle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Gypsy children the possibility that guarantees the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens", Járóka demanded.
The aim of the European Summit on Equality of Opportunities, which has been held annually since last year's Berlin meeting in the context of the European Year of Equality of Opportunities, is to ensure a single forum to promote the elimination of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
