It's an extinct deposit that occupies over 70% of the planet's surface and is now being discovered by the world's biggest energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources that big people like Chevron look up to.
The possibility of energy harvesting from sea movements has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s together with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was put aside, but now that environmental issues and the new rise in oil are giving the sector momentum.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated that by 2007 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be met by implants that exploit the movement of sea waves.
This would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there'd be the currents and the tides.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build an implant in northern Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away, more and more companies are betting on marine energy and among these companies are those who have always voted for traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technology", a spokesman for a company associated with the US oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us".
The cooperation in question is about obtaining permission from the U.S. Energy Commission to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It's a pretty important signal, considering that in Alaska the US continues to mine oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to drill new wells.
In addition to Chevron's Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey following the path of energy coming from the sea, the total invested so far, although not detailed, indicate an increasing interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still in its infancy, because marine energy has no doubt a great environmental impact.
For now, impacts like those of the Portuguese or the Scots are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, a technology with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the options are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boas joined together.
The force of the waves, which moves the boas up and down, becomes hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
The pressure drives a turbine that in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent to the coast via submarine cables.
There are currently four such implants under development, pending only federal approval, apart from the energy, that could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot, using underwater turbines on New York's East River.
The movement of water when there is tides, causes the turbine pads to spin, creating a rotating motion that powers the generator.
Verdant has said he has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Development of Electrical Energy, deserves at this time the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
It's mostly about tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, together with others that are approaching the shores, have invested $7.5 million in 2008 and an investment of $35 million is planned for 2009.
